        5 comments
    </a>
    
    
    </p>
</div>




<h2>
    <a href="/blog/constructing-reuleaux-polygons/">Constructing Reuleaux polygons</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    
    on 21 Jun 2018
</h6>





<a href="/blog/constructing-reuleaux-polygons/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/reuleaux/.thumbnails/reuleaux-3.png/reuleaux-3-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>A <a href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/ReuleauxPolygon.html">Reuleaux polygon</a> is a curvilinear polygon built up of circular arcs. For an odd number of vertices, it has a constant width, and for this reason many polygonal coins, such as <a href="https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/seven-sides-of-a-50p-coin">the UK's 50p piece</a> and <a href="https://de.ucoin.net/coin/bermuda-1-dollar-1997/?tid=50025">this Bermudian dollar coin</a> are Reuleaux polygons. This property also means they make serviceable bicycle wheels:</p>




